    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Plot.XVsY">X vs Y</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.XCountVsTime">Each point is the raw DeltaX from one Raw Input report. Use it to spot horizontal micro-jitter, jumpy outliers, or abnormal spikes during fast swipes.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.YCountVsTime">Each point is the raw DeltaY from one Raw Input report. Use it to spot vertical noise, outliers, or unnatural spikes during upward and downward motion.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.XYCountVsTime">Shows DeltaX and DeltaY together for every report. Useful for comparing axis balance and finding single-axis noise, bias, or decoupling problems.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.IntervalVsTime">Each point is the gap from the previous report. Frequent spikes usually indicate report jitter, dropped packets, wireless instability, or scheduler stalls.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.FrequencyVsTime">Instantaneous report rate computed as 1000 / Interval. It helps verify that the mouse stays close to its rated polling rate instead of dipping or wavering.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.XVelocityVsTime">Horizontal speed derived from DeltaX / Interval / CPI. Use it to judge low-to-high speed linearity and to spot velocity-linked jitter or acceleration.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.YVelocityVsTime">Vertical speed derived from DeltaY / Interval / CPI. Use it to judge vertical speed linearity and whether one axis becomes unstable at higher speed.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.XYVelocityVsTime">Compares X and Y speed response together. Useful for checking axis consistency and whether one axis falls apart or fluctuates more under fast motion.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.XSumVsTime">Cumulative DeltaX over time. The slope reflects sustained horizontal output, while abrupt slope changes, flats, or reversals can reveal skipping or correction.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.YSumVsTime">Cumulative DeltaY over time. Useful for finding vertical stalls, compensation, or unexpected reversals during longer motion.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.XYSumVsTime">Cumulative DeltaX and DeltaY together. Useful for checking whether long movement remains smooth, synchronized, and free from single-axis drift.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.XVsY">Trajectory built from cumulative X and Y position. This is the best view for spotting angle snapping, line correction, wobble, axis bias, or imperfect circles.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.Semantics.RawLine">Scatter points are individual valid motion samples; the line connects the raw samples in arrival order so you can inspect jitter and outliers directly.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.Semantics.TrendLine">Scatter points are individual valid motion samples; the trend line uses a symmetric time window of about {0} ms to show the overall tendency rather than the sensor's internal firmware smoothing.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.Semantics.Trajectory">The trajectory view always shows the raw cumulative path inside the selected range. It is never smoothed, so shape defects and correction are easier to judge.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.Semantics.HostObserved">The time axis reflects host-observed Raw Input arrival behavior, not a device-side hardware clock. It is best used to judge the stability of the full input path.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="MousePerformance.Chart.Description.Semantics.Degraded">The current session has quality warnings: dropped packets {0}, out-of-order timestamps {1}, zero-interval samples {2}. If the waveform looks wrong, rule out transport or tool-side pressure first.</sys:String>
